            <h4 class=3D"t-question ">
              <span class=3D"q-txt">How is a Handicap Index calculated?</sp=
an>
              <span class=3D"icon">
                <svg width=3D"22" height=3D"22" viewBox=3D"0 0 22 22" fill=
=3D"none" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                  <path id=3D"v-line" d=3D"M1 11H21" stroke=3D"#0055A5" str=
oke-width=3D"2" stroke-linecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round"></path>
                  <path id=3D"h-line" d=3D"M11 21V1" stroke=3D"#0055A5" str=
oke-width=3D"2" stroke-linecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round"></path>
                </svg>
              </span>
            </h4>
            <div class=3D"t-answer ">
              <p>As a Handicap Index is intended to represent a golfer=E2=
=80=99s demonstrated ability, it is based on your better scores =E2=80=93 t=
he best 8 of your most recent 20.</p>
<p>Read more on USGA's Rules of Handicapping page:<span>&nbsp;</span><a hre=
f=3D"https://www.usga.org/content/usga/home-page/handicapping/roh/2020-rule=
s-of-handicapping.html#!rule-14389" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">Rule=
 5 Handicap Index Calculation</a><span>&nbsp;</span>for detailed informatio=
n on the rules and mathematics of handicapping.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-bottom: 30px;"><span>Rule 5 covers the process of calcul=
ating a Handicap Index and incorporates the safeguards needed to help ensur=
e that a player=E2=80=99s Handicap Index remains reflective of their abilit=
y and that equity is retained for all golfers. It includes mechanisms that:=
</span></p>
<ul>
<li>Take into consideration the conditions in which a round was played.</li=
>
<li>Remember previously demonstrated ability within a defined period of tim=
e.</li>
<li>Cap the upward movement of a player=E2=80=99s Handicap Index within a d=
efined period of time.</li>
<li>Apply additional adjustments to a player=E2=80=99s Handicap Index when =
an exceptional score is submitted.</li>
</ul>
