         =20
          <li class=3D"none text-body">
            <h4 class=3D"t-question ">
              <span class=3D"q-txt">What does =E2=80=98popping the scorecar=
d=E2=80=99 mean?</span>
              <span class=3D"icon">
                <svg width=3D"22" height=3D"22" viewBox=3D"0 0 22 22" fill=
=3D"none" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                  <path id=3D"v-line" d=3D"M1 11H21" stroke=3D"#0055A5" str=
oke-width=3D"2" stroke-linecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round"></path>
                  <path id=3D"h-line" d=3D"M11 21V1" stroke=3D"#0055A5" str=
oke-width=3D"2" stroke-linecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round"></path>
                </svg>
              </span>
            </h4>
            <div class=3D"t-answer ">
              <p>If you play in an event and give them your handicap, you m=
ay have seen little dots on the scorecard for each hole next to your name. =
This is for games when the net score for the hole is needed, or when you ar=
e playing match play or skins games.</p>
<p>The dots represent the number of strokes or pops that you are getting. I=
f your handicap is 14, you get 14 pops, 1 for each of the 14 toughest holes=
. If your handicap is 21, you get 1 pop for all 18 holes, then your last 3 =
pops get added as one more each for the 3 hardest holes.</p>
<p><img src=3D"https://ncga.org/hs-fs/hubfs/Poppy%20Hills%20Golf%20Course.p=
ng?width=3D600&amp;height=3D300&amp;name=3DPoppy%20Hills%20Golf%20Course.pn=
g" width=3D"600" height=3D"300" loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Poppy Hills Golf Co=
urse" style=3D"height: auto; max-width: 100%; width: 600px; margin-left: au=
to; margin-right: auto; display: block;"></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
            </div>
          </li>
         =20
          <li class=3D"none text-body">
            <h4 class=3D"t-question ">
              <span class=3D"q-txt">How do net tournaments and flights work=
?</span>
              <span class=3D"icon">
                <svg width=3D"22" height=3D"22" viewBox=3D"0 0 22 22" fill=
=3D"none" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                  <path id=3D"v-line" d=3D"M1 11H21" stroke=3D"#0055A5" str=
oke-width=3D"2" stroke-linecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round"></path>
                  <path id=3D"h-line" d=3D"M11 21V1" stroke=3D"#0055A5" str=
oke-width=3D"2" stroke-linecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round"></path>
                </svg>
              </span>
            </h4>
            <div class=3D"t-answer ">
              <h5>How do Net Tournaments work and what do the flights mean?=
</h5>
<p>Once you know the rules and have your handicap, you are ready to try out=
 some =E2=80=98Net Tournaments=E2=80=99. All the scores are adjusted to net=
 scores, so you are just trying to play as well as you can vs. your handica=
p level. In the example above, you have a 30 handicap and you score 105. If=
 the course is a par-72 course, your net score is 105-30=3D75, not bad. Tha=
t=E2=80=99s just 3 strokes over par and could get you prizes.</p>
<p>Flights are your friend! Flights are set up by handicap, so you will nor=
mally compete against players with a similar handicap. Since you are all on=
 a similar footing, it can be an enjoyable experience. Many people meet new=
 golf friends in this way.</p>
<p>Again, the magic of the handicap system. Golfers at every handicap level=
 can enjoy playing in tournaments.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
         =20
          <li class=3D"none text-body">
            <h4 class=3D"t-question ">
              <span class=3D"q-txt">What is the maximum Handicap Index?</sp=
an>
              <span class=3D"icon">
                <svg width=3D"22" height=3D"22" viewBox=3D"0 0 22 22" fill=
=3D"none" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                  <path id=3D"v-line" d=3D"M1 11H21" stroke=3D"#0055A5" str=
oke-width=3D"2" stroke-linecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round"></path>
                  <path id=3D"h-line" d=3D"M11 21V1" stroke=3D"#0055A5" str=
oke-width=3D"2" stroke-linecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round"></path>
                </svg>
              </span>
            </h4>
            <div class=3D"t-answer ">
              <p>The maximum Handicap Index is 54.0 for all players.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
         =20
          <li class=3D"none text-body">
            <h4 class=3D"t-question ">
              <span class=3D"q-txt">What is Stableford in golf?</span>
              <span class=3D"icon">
                <svg width=3D"22" height=3D"22" viewBox=3D"0 0 22 22" fill=
=3D"none" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
                  <path id=3D"v-line" d=3D"M1 11H21" stroke=3D"#0055A5" str=
oke-width=3D"2" stroke-linecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round"></path>
                  <path id=3D"h-line" d=3D"M11 21V1" stroke=3D"#0055A5" str=
oke-width=3D"2" stroke-linecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round"></path>
                </svg>
              </span>
            </h4>
            <div class=3D"t-answer ">
              <p>Stableford is a points-based scoring format where, instead=
 of counting your total number of strokes, you earn points on each hole bas=
ed on how well you play relative to par. Here=E2=80=99s the basic breakdown=
:<br><br><strong>Double bogey or worse</strong>: 0 points<br><strong>Bogey<=
/strong>: 1 point<br><strong>Par</strong>: 2 points<br><strong>Birdie</stro=
ng>: 3 points<br><strong>Eagle</strong>: 4 points<br><strong>Albatross</str=
ong> (you legend): 5 points<br><br>The beauty? You can pick up your ball af=
ter a blow-up hole because you=E2=80=99re not penalized with a giant number=
 =E2=80=94 you just get zero points and move on. That means faster play, le=
ss frustration, and more focus on bouncing back.</p>
<h4 data-start=3D"1501" data-end=3D"1551">Why Stableford Matters for Your H=
andicap Index</h4>
<p><span><strong>Stableford scoring is built into the World Handicap System=
.</strong></span></p>
<ul>
<li>The World Handicap System (WHS) uses <strong>maximum hole scores</stron=
g> (net double bogey) when you're posting your score hole-by-hole. That mea=
ns really bad holes don=E2=80=99t drag down your Handicap Index too much.</=
li>
<li>In effect, WHS already gives you a bit of that Stableford protection be=
hind the scenes.</li>
<li>If you don=E2=80=99t yet have a Handicap Index, <a href=3D"https://ncga=
.org/become-ncga-member?hsLang=3Den" rel=3D"noopener">joining NCGA</a> gets=
 you access to features (like GHIN app, score posting) that work with this =
system.</li>
</ul>
